  "prompt": "If a local host has multiple IP addresses, which interface does the ssh client use to start a connection?",
  "response": "When a local host has multiple IP addresses, the SSH client typically follows these rules to select an interface:\n\n1. By default, the SSH client will:\n- Use the default route's primary network interface\n- Select the IP address associated with that interface\n- Use the routing table to determine the most appropriate outgoing interface\n\n2. You can manually specify the source IP/interface using SSH client options:\n- Use `-b <source_ip>` to bind to a specific source address\n- Use `-I <interface_name>` in some SSH implementations to specify an interface\n\n3. Factors influencing interface selection:\n- Routing table metrics\n- Interface priority\n- Destination network reachability\n- Network configuration\n\n4. The selection process generally follows the system's routing rules, choosing the most efficient path to the destination.\n\nThe exact behavior can vary slightly depending on the operating system and specific network configuration.\n\nIf you need precise control, you can:\n- Configure routing policy\n- Use explicit source IP binding\n- Modify routing table\n- Configure interface priorities\n\nThe key principle is that the system's routing mechanism determines the default interface unless explicitly overridden.",
